Oil markets experience large fluctuations and periods of increased uncertainty.
This project studies volatility in the globalcrude oil benchmarks West Texas Intermediate (WTI) and/or Brent (COIL). 

This project studies volatility in crude oil markets using Bayesian methods. I analyze daily prices of crude oil benchmarks obtained from the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis FRED database for WTI or, alternatively, an open-source csv file tracking Brent. After converting prices to log returns, I hope to use two Bayesian models: a simple normal return model and a heavy-tailed model. Posterior inference will be computed using two different approaches: a basic Metropolis–Hastings MCMC sampler and perhaps a Hamiltonian Monte Carlo. I will compare these approaches using effective sample size, convergence diagnostics, and computational efficiency. The goal is to evaluate whether heavy-tailed models provide a better description of oil price fluctuations and to assess the efficiency gains of modern Bayesian computation methods.


