# Scientific Question(s)

This project will address the following questions:

- What is the estimated volatility of daily oil price returns?

- Do oil returns exhibit heavy tails relative to a normal distribution?

- Does a more flexible model improve the fit to the observed return distribution?

- How do different Bayesian computation methods compare in terms of efficiency and convergence?

## Bayesian Models

Two models will be considered.

### Model 1: Normal Return Model (Baseline)

This model assumes that returns follow a normal distribution with constant volatility.

$$
r_t \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma)
$$

**Priors**

$$
\mu \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)
$$

$$
\sigma \sim \text{Half-Cauchy}(0, 2.5)
$$

---

### Model 2: Student-t Return Model (Heavy-Tailed)

This model allows for heavy tails, which are common in financial return data.

$$r_t \sim N(\mu, \sigma)$$

where:

- \( \mu \) is the mean return  
- \( \sigma \) is the scale parameter  
- \( \nu \) controls the heaviness of the tails  

**Priors**

\[
\mu \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)
\]

\[
\sigma \sim \text{Half-Cauchy}(0, 2.5)
\]

\[
\nu \sim \text{Exponential}(1)
\]

Posterior Computation

The posterior distribution will be computed using two different methods.

Method 1:  Metropolis–Hastings sampler


Method 2: Hamiltonian Monte Carlo

Posterior sampling will also be performed using Stan, which implements Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC).


## Comparison of Methods

The two sampling methods will be compared using:

- Effective sample size

- Convergence diagnostics (trace plots, etc.)

- Posterior variance estimates

- Computational time


